  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\nB_{\\partial\\Omega}\\phi\n=\n\\sum_n b_n(\\partial\\Omega)\\,\\phi_n .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Coefficient Decomposition.}\n\\begin{equation}\nb_n\n=\nb_n^{\\mathrm{geom}}\n+\nb_n^{\\mathrm{top}}\n+\nb_n^{\\mathrm{curv}} .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nFrom mode quantization, a confined field can be expanded as:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\phi=\\sum_n \\phi_n .\n\\end{equation}\n\nBoundary geometry modifies the amplitude or phase of each mode through coefficients $b_n(\\partial\\Omega)$.\n\nThe boundary-response operator is therefore:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\nB_{\\partial\\Omega}\\phi\n=\n\\sum_n b_n(\\partial\\Omega)\\,\\phi_n .\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe coefficient naturally decomposes into geometric, topological, and curvature components:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nb_n\n=\nb_n^{\\mathrm{geom}}\n+\nb_n^{\\mathrm{top}}\n+\nb_n^{\\mathrm{curv}} .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nBoundaries actively reshape quantum fields by reweighting their confined mode expansion.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
